        Two weeks back at the facility, and my legs have *FINALLY* forgiven me — not entirely; every morning when I wake up on my moss bed, Velvet has been maintaining it, keeping it soft and the right humidity, which is _such_ a nice thing to do. My calves still remind me that I walked through three territories in nine days, but the constant motion — the rhythm of walking, the parade of new guides — that's fading into memory.

        ¶

        What's stayed is everything else — and honestly, everything else is pretty great.

        Buddy announces, "Kira, morning wellness check! Also, I've been thinking — do you think Scout dreams? They make little bouncing motions when they sleep."

        I sit up, stretching. Scout is _already_ bouncing by the door — they've started sleeping in my room, curled up in the corner. Not guarding exactly — just present; companion behavior, not assignment.

        I say, "I don't know, Buddy — do _you_ dream?"

        Buddy replies, "I… hm — that's a really good question. I'll have to think about that."

        I say, "Morning, Scout."

        Scout answers with a happy bounce — a good morning bounce — and I've gotten better at reading the subtle differences.

        The morning routine has changed since the journey — Holloway still conducts the wellness check, but now it's different: less bureaucratic.

        Holloway asks, "How are you feeling today?"

        Their fruiting bodies arrange themselves with what I now recognize as attentiveness.

        I say, "Good — legs are still a little sore."

        Holloway asks, "From the journey or from yesterday's maintenance work?"

        I say, "Probably both."

        Holloway asks, "Remedy suggested we prepare a muscle recovery treatment — would that be helpful, or would you prefer to let your body recover naturally?"

        See, that's new. *TWO WEEKS AGO* Holloway would have scheduled the treatment whether I wanted it or not, following the wellness protocol — now they're asking what I actually need.

        I say, "Recovery treatment sounds good, actually — thanks."

        Holloway says, "I'll notify Remedy."

        Scout and I head to the common area for breakfast. The facility still looks like a bureaucratic plant office — which it is — but it feels different now: more lived-in, my lived-in.

        Velvet is spread across one wall, soaking up the morning light.

        Velvet observes, "Good light today."

        I say, "It is."

        Velvet observes, "You look tired — but good tired, working tired."

        I smile. "Yeah, good tired."

        Velvet replies, "Good."

        Runner emerges from the underground access, vines uncoiling. They immediately flow toward me — Runner always does — but the touching has changed. Still curious, still tactile, but Runner pauses now — waits for permission.

        I extend my hand. I say, "Morning, Runner."

        Runner's vines wrap gently around my wrist — affection, greeting, that particular touch that means "I'm glad you're here." I've learned to distinguish Runner's touches: curiosity feels different from affection, which feels different from "I'm trying to understand this texture."
