    At one point Scout returns from circling the perimeter—something they've started doing regularly—and bounces differently. Agitated. Not the happy bounce or the discovery bounce, something tighter. They circle the common area twice, then settle near the eastern wall, watching.

    I ask, "What's wrong, Scout?"

    But Scout just bounces once—uncertain—and keeps watching. I don't know how to read this bounce yet. Something's bothering them, but I can't understand what.

    Velvet observes quietly, "Scout's been doing that for a few days—checking the boundaries. Coming back… tense."

    I file it away to think about later. Maybe Scout just needs more exploration time.

    We're good at it now—that realization hits me as I'm helping Runner organize the supply storage. We're actually good at this. The plants understand my needs better, I understand their frameworks, and we've built a functional rhythm.

    «And I'm… happy?»

    I stop what I'm doing, caught off guard by the feeling. When did that happen? I catch myself humming—actually humming—while sorting nutrient packets.

    I say quietly, "Buddy—how long has it been since I asked you about rescue timelines?"

    Buddy says, "Seventeen days. I noticed you stopped checking. I wasn't sure if I should mention it."

    «I haven't thought about rescue in *SEVENTEEN* days?»

    «That's… huh. That's actually kind of huge.»

    I say slowly, "Runner—have you noticed things are working better?"

    Runner agrees immediately, "Yes—cooperation is smoother. Communication clearer. We're learning your patterns, you're learning—this one has a crack. Tiny. Can barely feel it. Anyway—learning ours."

    Runner's vines wrap gently around a storage container, organizing it precisely by some texture-based logic I don't quite follow.

    Small adjustments that compound—that's exactly what it feels like.

    That evening, gathered in the common area, Holloway brings up what's on everyone's mind.

    Holloway flutes, "Elder Heartwood's response should arrive soon. Another week, perhaps two."

    There's a collective sense of anticipation—the plants are hopeful, excited even.

    Holloway says confidently, "Elder Heartwood will provide the framework we need — the systematic understanding of human care that we've been missing."

    Florence adds, "It will explain the patterns — connect the individual solutions we've found into a coherent whole."

    Scout bounces — agreement, excitement. I do want to share their enthusiasm.

    «Do we actually need Elder Heartwood to tell us how to do what we're already doing?» I think, sitting here and looking around at the plants who've been helping me, remembering everything we've figured out together…

    The thought feels almost disloyal. The plants have so much faith in Elder Heartwood's wisdom. They journeyed three territories to present the question — they've been waiting weeks for the response; they're counting on this.

    And maybe Elder Heartwood *WILL* have useful insights — ancient wisdom, vast perspective, understanding that connects everything.

    But also… we've been learning the real answers every day through trial and error and by paying attention to each other: the muscle-recovery paste Remedy refined based on my feedback; Runner's growing understanding of boundaries; Holloway asking what I need instead of scheduling what the manual recommends; Velvet's deepening observations; Scout's companionship — those are real, those are working.

    Holloway continues, "When the response comes — we'll finally understand how to properly care for you, Kira. The uncertainty will resolve."

    Everyone seems so sure — so hopeful. I don't want to undermine that. They've worked hard, they care deeply, they've been waiting for this answer.

    But I'm also starting to realize we might not need it the way they think we do.

    I say carefully, "I'm sure it will be helpful." Which is probably true — even if it's not the answer they're hoping for, Elder Heartwood's perspective might offer something useful, maybe.

    Scout curls up next to me, content. Velvet comments, "The evening light is particularly good today." Runner asks, "Can we check the ventilation system tomorrow? There's a section that might need repair."

    This is my life now — daily maintenance with plant companions who are learning to care for me while I learn to work with them. We're not waiting for the real answer to arrive — we're already living it.

    But tomorrow, or next week, or whenever Elder Heartwood's response comes, I'll find out if the plants can see that too.
